The paper deals with graph problems and their online versions, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the trade-off between the amount of advice given to the algorithm and its performance, which is a topic of interest in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The paper also uses graph theory concepts such as hereditary and cohereditary properties, which are studied in the subfield of graph theory (cs.GT) and combinatorics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper discusses the use of online algorithms in decision-making, which is a topic of interest in artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
